<br>
With the losses we've all taken to DAoC, we've kept our eyes open for folks we like who have suddenly found themselves &quot;homeless&quot; in Norrath.  It's a win-win because we now can do some of the things we were able to do before the DAoC slump, all of us.  Not trying to build &quot;uber&quot;, just maintain our FUN factor.  We still look for the immediate feeling that here are people who will be FUN to be with, who feel like friends almost immediately.<br>
<br>
Capt. Obvious makes a good point.  I did a tour of duty as a guildmaster, and few truly realize the time and effort required to move a guild in any way, shape, or form.  If the guild has good people, it's worth it, but it can put a real damper on FUN in Norrath.  <br>
<br>
Given the situation you seem to be saying you are in, the key is being able to say it was worth it before the hard times hit.  What has helped us was that the answer was yes, and that how many RR's there were never mattered to us, just that we were.  Being a guild coming up on a three year anniversary hasn't hurt either.<br>
